e New York Times", "subsection_name": "Sunday Review", "lead_paragraph": "The ancient structures that the Islamic State destroyed in Iraq and Syria were not just relics.", "pub_date": "2016-03-20T00:00:00Z", "news_desk": "OpEd", "headline": {"kicker": "Opinion", "print_headline": "Life Among the Ruins", "main": "Life Among the Ruins", "content_kicker": "Opinion"}, "print_page": "5", "snippet": "The ancient structures that the Islamic State destroyed in Iraq and Syria were not just relics.", "_id": "56ed9ab638f0d811b85b0cf2", "slideshow_credits": null, "abstract": "Op-Ed article by BBC Radio host Kanishk Tharoor underscores importance of cultural context of ancient ruins like Temple of Baal, destroyed by Islamic State when group rampaged through Syrian town of Palmyra; notes while reproduction of temple's entrance will be installed in New York and London, exhibits will not capture what ruins mean to people who literally have lived within them; suggests it is important to think of such at-risk heritage sites in Iraq and Syria within such a rich social context."}